Anonymous Fri 22 Feb 2019 14:21:41 No.21460010 Report
Quoted By: >>21460038 >>21460124 >>21461041
>>21455494
Careful with your punctuation and capitalization. A few times you forgot to capitalize I, I'm and I've, and you capitalized turtleneck when it didn't need it. In general its tone feels a bit rushed, you use a lot of commas where it could stand to have full stops or hyphens. Examples I noticed are on line 17 and 38.

On the same note, you should try and picture your writing as though you're leading someone around with a camera. Describe something with a sentence - or two or as many as you need - then end the sentence before you move on to describing someone else. Ideally, each item should relate to the next in some way so the viewer has a clear connection of where you're going.
For example on line 13: "You grab the key, the Kobold now standing next to you, at least not in the freezing cold now." This one sentence brings up 3 points of interest, and should be a bit more carefully separated. "You grab the key and look down at the Kobold whose shackles it unlocks. It has picked itself up and is now shivering as it stands next to you - at least it's in out of the cold now, so it may be able to warm up."

1/2
Anonymous
  • Post
  • Report

Anonymous Fri 22 Feb 2019 14:24:23 No.21460038 Report
Quoted By: >>21461041
>>21460010
You should also try and hint at why something is important when you bring it up. Most sentences should relate back to the characters, and what you want the viewer to think of them - they're the centrepiece of the story, it's all about them. For example, on line 26 - "Walking over to the table you see Lucco staring at all painting of you and your family." This simply describes what the character is doing, but you can really let the reader into their head by hinting why they do it, or what it means for them. A few examples:
"Walking over to the table, you see Lucco examining at a painting of you and your family, a look of longing showing clear on her face." This makes the character more emotional - it quietly tells the reader they either miss their family or never had one, but wish they did.
"Walking over to the table, you see Lucco studying at a painting of you and your family with a shrewd look in its eye." This frames the character up as cunning, resilient, looking for a weakness they might exploit to escape.

Make sure when you're describing someone doing something that you have first solidly stated what they are doing, and be sure not to do this for the Anon character who holds the perspective. Examples are on line 8 - ", heading towards to shop's door." should be its own sentence - "You head toward the shop's door". And on line 17 - "The Kobold seemingly analyzing you for any dishonesty." should be something like "The Kobold scrutinizes you carefully, seemingly analyzing you for any dishonesty."

Also, be mindful of accidentally changing tense like was done twice on line 11.

tl;dr A really good foundation. You've got a good eye for painting the scene, but you could stand to walk a bit slower through it and guide the reader around a bit more carefully. Spread your descriptions out over a sentence or two extra, and relate them back to the characters. Lastly, don't forget to be mindful of grammatical/punctuational errors.

Hope this all helps.

Anonymous Fri 22 Feb 2019 22:33:01 No.21467716 Report
Quoted By: >>21467808 >>21467892 >>21467946 >>21468212
And one last quick edit before bed

>>21467541
What you should do is select roughly the area you want to change leaving a bit of margin around it but not too much, then making it into a new layer via copy.
Once you have your new layer you take some kind of reference drawing with nice looking human skin in it, select an area that contains a proportional amount of all the skins different shades and make it into a new layer via cut.
Now you use match colour to match your copied destination layer to your cut sampled layer.
Your margin will inevitably look weird but that's why you then erase it manually, making sure to set your erasers opacity to around 60% and hardness to around 85% to get a nice smooth looking edge (multiple passes will be required though).
To get better results, set your brush size really high and just use the edge of the brush to nip at eh edges of what you want to erase, you'll get more even lines this way.

If you're dealing with a character with multiple fur colors, make each fur color it's own copied layer matching each separately, the edges will inevitably look weird or be mismatched so use either a brush with a colour sampled from the surrounding area or the clone stamp tool if there's texture with their hardness and opacity turned way down (around 20% opacity and 40% hardness). You're going to have to do a fuck-ton of passes to build up the colour but the results will be much smoother. Make sure to regularly re-sample from the area your working in to maintain consistency and to achieve good color blending.

All of this should be done after you've fully redrawn the image to get rid of fur, claws, muzzles, digit grade feet and so on.
Redrawing is just something you have to learn, there's no shortcut there. Best you can do is to try and crop as much as possible.

The clone stamp is going to be your most powerful tool for fixing most anything, it's going to be the main way to rebuild backgrounds in areas where you've had to erase tails, ears, etc.

Some other pointers:
When matching colours you'll probably have to play around with the colour intensity and luminescence to get things just right, if it's still too pink consider adding an all orange layer and making it a clipping mask, and then playing with the opacity until it looks right.
Cum and white highlights don't play nice with colour match, a trick you can do is to take your copied layer just before you would normally colour match, create a duplicate layer, smooth over all the white areas on the first layer (cum etc.) using the clone stamp or a smooth brush so it's all just the same tone as the surroundings, and then after colour matching that set the copied layer as a screen (or something else, you might have to test a little) in the blending options and you'll have much more natural cum stains.
